** Garbage Collection (GC) in Java is a memory management mechanism that automatically removes objects that are no longer used by the program, freeing heap memory.
1) How Garbage Collection Works in Java
In Java, objects are created in the Heap Memory.
When objects are no longer referenced by any part of the program, they become eligible for garbage collection.

class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Test obj = new Test(); // object created
        obj = null;            // reference removed
    }
}

Java Memory Structure (Heap): The Java heap is divided into generations:
Heap Memory
------------
Young Generation
   |-- Eden
   |-- Survivor S0
   |-- Survivor S1

Old Generation
   |-- Long-lived objects

Metaspace
   |-- Class metadata

Workflow
    Objects are created in Eden space.
    If they survive garbage collection, they move to Survivor spaces.
    Long-lived objects move to the Old Generation.
    GC periodically removes unreachable objects.

Types of Garbage Collection
  1) Minor GC
    Cleans Young Generation
    Fast
    Happens frequently
  2) Major GC / Full GC
    Cleans Old Generation
    Slower
    Can cause Stop-The-World pauses




Important Garbage Collectors in Modern Java
Java provides multiple collectors:
    1) Serial GC
    2) Parallel GC
    3) CMS (deprecated)
    4) G1 Garbage Collector
    5) Z Garbage Collector
Currently G1 and ZGC are widely used.

G1 Garbage Collector (Garbage First): G1 GC was introduced to handle large heaps with predictable pauses.
*** Instead of fixed generations, G1 divides heap into small regions.
Heap
---------------------------------
| R1 | R2 | R3 | R4 | R5 | R6 |
---------------------------------
Some regions contain:
    Young objects
    Old objects

How G1 Works
    Heap divided into regions (1–32MB).
    GC identifies regions with most garbage.
    Cleans those regions first (Garbage First).
    Performs incremental collection.
Advantages
    ✔ Predictable pause times [~50–200 ms]
    ✔ Works well for large heaps (4GB+)
    ✔ Default GC since Java 9

Disadvantages
    ❌ Slightly higher CPU usage
    ❌ Not the lowest latency


ZGC (Z Garbage Collector)
    ZGC is designed for extremely low latency applications.
    Goal: Pause time < 10 milliseconds even for huge heaps.

Key Features
    Concurrent GC
    Colored pointers
    Load barriers
*** Most work happens while the application is running.

ZGC Workflow
    Mark objects concurrently
    Relocate objects concurrently
    Update references with minimal pause

Pause time is almost constant, regardless of heap size.





